"# Chapter 14 — Positional encoding and causal masking

Attention has two problems we glossed over. This chapter fixes them.

**Problem 1.** Attention treats a sequence like a set. If you shuffle
the token embeddings before feeding them to attention, the outputs
just shuffle by the same permutation. That means the model has no
idea what order the tokens came in. 'Dog bites man' and 'man bites
dog' would be indistinguishable — same tokens, different meaning.

**Problem 2.** During training we want to teach the model to predict
the next token given the previous ones. If we feed the whole
sequence into attention, position i can 'see' positions i+1, i+2,
etc. — the answer is right there. The model would learn nothing.

Positional encoding solves problem 1. Causal masking solves problem 2.

## Positional encoding — giving the model a sense of order

The idea: add a position-dependent vector to each token embedding
BEFORE it goes into the attention layers. Position 0 gets one vector.
Position 1 gets a different one. The model can then look at the sum
and figure out both 'what token is this' and 'where in the sequence
is it.'

The original transformer used SINUSOIDAL positional encoding. Each
dimension of the position vector is a sine or cosine of position at
a different frequency:

```
PE(pos, 2i)   = sin(pos / 10000^(2i/d))
PE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(pos / 10000^(2i/d))
```

Where pos is the position (0, 1, 2, ...) and i is the dimension
index. Different dimensions oscillate at different rates. Low
dimensions oscillate slowly (they encode which 'chapter' of the
sequence). High dimensions oscillate fast (they encode fine position).

## Problem 1 — Sinusoidal positional encoding

```
(define (sinusoidal-pos pos d)
  ;; Return a d-dim vector encoding position pos.
  (vec/make
    (map (lambda (i)
           (let ((exponent (/ (* 2 (quotient i 2)) d)))
             (let ((angle (/ pos (math/pow 10000 exponent))))
               (if (even? i) (math/sin angle) (math/cos angle)))))
         (iota d))))

(display (sinusoidal-pos 0 4))
;; => (sin(0/1) cos(0/1) sin(0/100) cos(0/100))
;; => (0 1 0 1)

(display (sinusoidal-pos 1 4))
;; => (sin(1) cos(1) sin(0.01) cos(0.01))
;; => (~0.841 ~0.540 ~0.01 ~1.0)

(display (sinusoidal-pos 10 4))
;; => (sin(10) cos(10) sin(0.1) cos(0.1))
;; => (~-0.544 ~-0.839 ~0.0998 ~0.995)
```

Different positions produce different vectors. Adjacent positions are
similar in the slow dimensions, different in the fast dimensions. The
model can learn to read these.

## Problem 2 — Add positional encoding to embeddings

Very simple. Element-wise addition.

```
(define (add-positions embeddings)
  (define d (vec/dim (car embeddings)))
  (define seq-len (length embeddings))
  (map (lambda (i emb)
         (vec/add emb (sinusoidal-pos i d)))
       (iota seq-len)
       embeddings))

;; If your token embeddings are tok-embs, feed
;; (add-positions tok-embs) to the transformer instead.
```

That is the entire positional-encoding step. Token embeddings +
position encoding = position-aware embeddings. The transformer layers
never need to know about position specifically — the information is
baked into the vectors.

## Learned vs sinusoidal

Modern transformers (BERT, GPT) often use LEARNED positional
embeddings — just an embedding table indexed by position, updated by
gradient descent like everything else. Same shape as token
embeddings, learned in the same way. Slightly better empirical
performance; more parameters. Both work.

A newer alternative — RoPE (rotary positional encoding) used by
Llama and others — encodes position via rotations applied inside the
attention. It generalizes better to sequences longer than the model
was trained on. For our tiny LLM, sinusoidal or a small learned
table are fine.

## Causal masking — no peeking at the future

Now the training-time problem. When we train a language model, the
task is 'given tokens 0..i, predict token i+1.' If attention at
position i can see positions i+1, i+2, etc., the model can just copy
the answer.

The fix is to MASK OUT future positions in the attention. Specifically,
before the softmax, we set the scores for future positions to
negative infinity. After softmax, those positions have weight zero.
The model literally cannot see them.

```
;; A causal mask matrix M for sequence length n:
;;   M[i][j] = 0 if j <= i
;;   M[i][j] = -infinity if j > i
;; Add M to the scores BEFORE softmax.

(define (causal-mask-value i j)
  (if (<= j i) 0 -10000000000.0))    ;; -10000000000.0 acts as -infinity for float practice

(define (masked-attention q keys values i)
  (define d-k (vec/dim (car keys)))
  (define scale (math/sqrt d-k))
  (define raw-scores (map (lambda (k) (/ (vec/dot q k) scale)) keys))
  (define masked-scores
    (map (lambda (score j) (+ score (causal-mask-value i j)))
         raw-scores
         (iota (length raw-scores))))
  (define weights (softmax masked-scores))
  (fold vec/add
        (vec/scale (car values) 0)
        (map (lambda (w v) (vec/scale v w)) weights values)))
```

At position i, all future positions get score -10000000000.0 added. `exp(-10000000000.0)`
is essentially zero. After softmax, all future positions have weight
zero. Only positions 0..i contribute to the output.

## Problem 3 — Verify masking works

Verify by counting nonzero attention weights.

```
(define (softmax xs)
  (define m (fold (lambda (a b) (if (> a b) a b)) (car xs) (cdr xs)))
  (define exps (map (lambda (x) (math/exp (- x m))) xs))
  (define s (reduce + 0 exps))
  (map (lambda (e) (/ e s)) exps))

(define q (list 1 0))
(define keys (list (list 1 0))
                   (list 0 1))
                   (list 1 1))
                   (list 0 0))))

;; From position 1: can see positions 0 and 1, not 2 or 3.
(define d-k 2)
(define raw-scores (map (lambda (k) (/ (vec/dot q k) (math/sqrt d-k))) keys))
(define masked (map (lambda (s j) (if (<= j 1) s -10000000000.0))
                    raw-scores (iota 4)))
(display (softmax masked))
;; => (some positive, some positive, ~0, ~0)
;; Positions 2 and 3 got weight ~0 as required.
```

Read the output. The first two weights are nonzero (positions 0 and 1
are allowed). The last two are essentially zero (positions 2 and 3
are masked). Position 1's attention literally cannot see the future.

## Problem 4 — Training with causal masking

During training we feed a whole sequence into the model. The model
produces a sequence of predictions — position i's prediction of what
token comes next. We compare each prediction to the actual next
token, sum the losses, backpropagate.

The masking ensures that position i's prediction only used positions
0..i to produce it. So the loss at position i measures 'given the
first i+1 tokens, how well did the model predict token i+2.' Summed
over all positions, this trains the model on many next-token
predictions in parallel — one per position in the sequence. Very
efficient use of the data.

```
;; Pseudo-training-step:
;;   input_tokens = [t0, t1, t2, ..., tn]
;;   embeddings = [embed(t0), ...] + positional_encoding
;;   hidden = transformer_blocks(embeddings, with causal mask)
;;   logits = project hidden to vocab dimension
;;   for each position i:
;;     loss_i = cross-entropy(logits[i], t[i+1])
;;   total_loss = sum of loss_i
;;   backprop and update
```

Every token except the last one contributes to training. That is
what a next-token-prediction language model learns from.

## Problem 5 — Bidirectional models don't mask

BERT and its family use BIDIRECTIONAL attention — no causal mask.
Every position can see every other position. They train on a
different task: mask out some tokens and predict them from the
surrounding context (masked language modeling). Both directions
matter for that task.

GPT and its family use CAUSAL attention. Only left-to-right. That
makes them natural next-token predictors and text generators.

Our tiny LLM in chapter 16 is causal — we want to generate text.

## Capstone — Position-aware causally-masked attention

Combine everything from this chapter into one working attention
call.

```
(define (softmax xs)
  (define m (fold (lambda (a b) (if (> a b) a b)) (car xs) (cdr xs)))
  (define exps (map (lambda (x) (math/exp (- x m))) xs))
  (define s (reduce + 0 exps))
  (map (lambda (e) (/ e s)) exps))

(define (sinusoidal-pos pos d)
  (vec/make
    (map (lambda (i)
           (let ((exponent (/ (* 2 (quotient i 2)) d)))
             (let ((angle (/ pos (math/pow 10000 exponent))))
               (if (even? i) (math/sin angle) (math/cos angle)))))
         (iota d))))

(define (add-positions embeddings)
  (define d (vec/dim (car embeddings)))
  (define seq-len (length embeddings))
  (map (lambda (i emb) (vec/add emb (sinusoidal-pos i d)))
       (iota seq-len) embeddings))

(define (causal-masked-attention embeddings W-q W-k W-v)
  (define positioned (add-positions embeddings))
  (define d (vec/dim (car positioned)))
  (define scale (math/sqrt d))
  (define (matvec rows v) (map (lambda (r) (vec/dot r v)) rows))
  (define qs (map (lambda (x) (vec/make (matvec W-q x))) positioned))
  (define ks (map (lambda (x) (vec/make (matvec W-k x))) positioned))
  (define vs (map (lambda (x) (vec/make (matvec W-v x))) positioned))
  ;; For each position i, compute masked attention
  (map (lambda (i q)
         (let* ((raw (map (lambda (k) (/ (vec/dot q k) scale)) ks))
                (masked (map (lambda (s j) (if (<= j i) s -10000000000.0))
                             raw (iota (length ks))))
                (weights (softmax masked)))
           (fold vec/add
                 (vec/scale (car vs) 0)
                 (map (lambda (w v) (vec/scale v w)) weights vs))))
       (iota (length qs)) qs))

;; Try it on a random small sequence
(define d 4)
(define I (list (list 1 0 0 0))
                (list 0 1 0 0))
                (list 0 0 1 0))
                (list 0 0 0 1))))
(define embs (list (list 0.5 0.1 0.2 0.3))
                   (list 0.3 0.6 0.1 0.0))
                   (list 0.1 0.2 0.7 0.0))))

(display (causal-masked-attention embs I I I))
;; Three output vectors of dim 4.
;; Position 0: only saw position 0 (its output is close to its own value projection)
;; Position 1: saw positions 0 and 1
;; Position 2: saw positions 0, 1, 2
```

Position matters. Future is hidden. This is the exact attention
mechanism used in every GPT-family model. In chapter 16 we wire it
into a small transformer and train it on a paragraph of text.

## Why this matters

Position and masking are what turn a bag-of-vectors attention
mechanism into a proper sequence model. Without position, the model
can't distinguish word orders. Without causal masking, the training
is trivial (the model can copy the answer). Both are one-line fixes
that change the model qualitatively.

## What's next

Chapter 15 covers two more prerequisites for chapter 16's tiny LLM:
stacking multiple transformer blocks (deep networks) and tokenizing
sensibly (BPE — byte-pair encoding). Then chapter 16 assembles the
whole thing.
")
